Git Workflow:

# 

<span key="6f33e3c810a942bbae875e97027bf3be"><span offset-key="6f33e3c810a942bbae875e97027bf3be:0">Git Workflow</span></span>

## 

<span key="a695ffe57060457da4bebaeea42224ba"><span offset-key="a695ffe57060457da4bebaeea42224ba:0">Lambda Labs Git Workflow</span></span>

<span key="d7fe33b789544ffa8e62943716c8b72e"><span offset-key="d7fe33b789544ffa8e62943716c8b72e:0">We have some guidelines while you are working at Lambda Labs that will help reduce the friction of working in teams. Git is one of our most valued tools as developers. And as such we have put together the following guide regarding a workflow that will help keep you organized as well as save your butt from time to time.</span></span>

### 

<span key="695c2b73cc984b04bce049ec25a62238"><span offset-key="695c2b73cc984b04bce049ec25a62238:0">Objective</span></span>

<span key="533c15322220481595c0fb7686902089"><span offset-key="533c15322220481595c0fb7686902089:0">We will walk through the basic steps of starting and finishing a feature or task in git and github.com.</span></span>

<span key="020f0474c6e44d3ea2ef3d485247b635">**Technologies**</span>

### 

<span key="0ce15851443247e8a0a337713c2b20f4"><span offset-key="0ce15851443247e8a0a337713c2b20f4:0">Getting Started</span></span>

<span key="b64b045b71134b35a92c804852f1a004"><span offset-key="b64b045b71134b35a92c804852f1a004:0">So, you're ready to start work on a new Trello card, let's get started</span></span>

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

<span key="35be39d1086c41d48a363f271382e82a"><span offset-key="35be39d1086c41d48a363f271382e82a:0">Obviously, you can't do anything with git until you’ve cloned the team repo. After that always make sure you start with a recent copy of the repo.</span></span>

1

<span key="c485bd95d3094e849ba03eb2dbc2d3e6"><span offset-key="c485bd95d3094e849ba03eb2dbc2d3e6:0"> &gt; git checkout main</span></span>

2

<span key="18aebe7375034e19b358b6cb349b4d7f"><span offset-key="18aebe7375034e19b358b6cb349b4d7f:0"> &gt; git pull origin main</span></span>

<img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-h7gdob r-10ptun7" />

Copied!

<span key="976bff3299554da6a1a06f79137d48ee"><span offset-key="976bff3299554da6a1a06f79137d48ee:0">So, to get started on your first task let’s make a branch. Making sure you are on the </span>`main`<span offset-key="976bff3299554da6a1a06f79137d48ee:2"> branch, start a new branch with a name that matches or correlates to the task you are about to begin. The trick here is to think beyond yourself when naming the branch, stay aligned with your Trello board so you </span>**AND**<span offset-key="976bff3299554da6a1a06f79137d48ee:4"> others can easily make sense of it.</span></span>

> <span key="02ea1e7f35f445b49486ec83bb137a2d"><span offset-key="02ea1e7f35f445b49486ec83bb137a2d:0">git checkout -b \[new\_branch\_name\]</span></span>

### 

<span key="e45f8c0b2e214445837cccd476fd76ed"><span offset-key="e45f8c0b2e214445837cccd476fd76ed:0">Sharing Is Good</span></span>

<span key="4da031bbffe34d519d9642b4701dd582"><span offset-key="4da031bbffe34d519d9642b4701dd582:0">Now you have a branch to make all your awesome commits to. However, since you just had your team in mind while naming the branch, let’s take a minute or two to do something extra nice for them. Let's us the “Early Pull Strategy” to allow team members to follow along but not be nagged by our ongoing commits. This is done simply by pushing our new branch to the </span>**origin**<span offset-key="4da031bbffe34d519d9642b4701dd582:2"> then create a draft </span>**PR**<span offset-key="4da031bbffe34d519d9642b4701dd582:4"> in GitHub.</span></span>

> <span key="e9910be52bb24167b9668b40b5b719d8"><span offset-key="e9910be52bb24167b9668b40b5b719d8:0">git push -u origin ${git\_current\_branch}</span></span>

<span key="b3de52f566ad48b19363fa0e2cb417b6"><span offset-key="b3de52f566ad48b19363fa0e2cb417b6:0">or</span></span>

> <span key="52d4243e0c264736ad329e09930cdbfe"><span offset-key="52d4243e0c264736ad329e09930cdbfe:0">git push --set-upstream origin ${git\_current\_branch}</span></span>

<img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1vzi8xi" />

<span key="18d36bb472bf43a4acb523753bea71d6"><span offset-key="18d36bb472bf43a4acb523753bea71d6:0">The -u (--set-upstream) will save the tracking info for the remote branch to your git config. Yay. Now you can easily push your commits to the remote branch by git push. Easy.</span></span>

<span key="ba7d1a68503a44b1a18987764eadab70"><span offset-key="ba7d1a68503a44b1a18987764eadab70:0">The next step is to create a draft PR </span>*(Pull Request)*<span offset-key="ba7d1a68503a44b1a18987764eadab70:2"> </span>**after you’ve created your first commit**<span offset-key="ba7d1a68503a44b1a18987764eadab70:4">. GitHub created this mode so that notifications will be turned off by default until you decide to turn off the draft and want to have the team give you a code review. Back when we traveled uphill both ways, we called this a WIP, putting these initials at the beginning of the title and we’d have to ignore notifications that had WIP in the title. 🤮 Now we have it good.</span></span>

<span key="b3ac6837fb1e4e1e8934ef452de40dab"><span offset-key="b3ac6837fb1e4e1e8934ef452de40dab:0">Making sure to use the template to provide a professional description (seriously copy the description from the Trello card, right) summarizing the actual work in the PR, let’s create a PR using the </span>**main**<span offset-key="b3ac6837fb1e4e1e8934ef452de40dab:2"> branch as the </span>**base**<span offset-key="b3ac6837fb1e4e1e8934ef452de40dab:4">.</span></span>

### 

<span key="240482e98a194305909818643d7607cf"><span offset-key="240482e98a194305909818643d7607cf:0">We have lift off</span></span>

<span key="4d95f6a5b67a49cf8a61f8eee79c41c2"><span offset-key="4d95f6a5b67a49cf8a61f8eee79c41c2:0">And just like that we’re ready to make some awesome software. Committing and pushing our code regularly are the habits worth having. Before we know it, we’ll be ready to take the PR out of draft mode.</span></span>

<img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1vzi8xi" />

<span key="c6a57e540d1745989b8200895b0f71df"><span offset-key="c6a57e540d1745989b8200895b0f71df:0">Do your best to be a great team member by making commit messages as succinct as possible. They don’t have to be elaborate, just to the point.</span></span>

<span key="fd0bc24abc484fbaa0f2c9668cb2ddc6">**One small step**</span>

<span key="f4139bf672a04e1d81a2b0357b6be5dd"><span offset-key="f4139bf672a04e1d81a2b0357b6be5dd:0">When you feel you’ve completed the task you’ve been working on it’s time to update the description, take the PR out of draft mode and make it </span>**“ready for review”**<span offset-key="f4139bf672a04e1d81a2b0357b6be5dd:2">.</span></span>

<span key="58e5090ecdfb4421888b31d11581840e"><span offset-key="58e5090ecdfb4421888b31d11581840e:0">And just like that, the team will be notified of the PR and they can start a review and it can be merged.</span></span>

<img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1vzi8xi" />

<span key="b16f36f34001496b99cea36caf0e7d9d"><span offset-key="b16f36f34001496b99cea36caf0e7d9d:0">Follow the team policy regarding the number of reviewers required before merging</span></span>

<span key="c2b57cfda92144428bd42c869a6d581a"><span offset-key="c2b57cfda92144428bd42c869a6d581a:0">It’s really good practice to take the time to make comments in the code, even if they are positive notes on good work your teammate did.</span></span>

### 

<span key="3df8ffe6354c41c38104eee2c9db554c"><span offset-key="3df8ffe6354c41c38104eee2c9db554c:0">QA changes on stage before merging to main</span></span>

<span key="0c47e0d852264bb49d04ab2ae2533bea"><span offset-key="0c47e0d852264bb49d04ab2ae2533bea:0">Since you branched off of main your PR should be tested on stage prior to approving and merging. If there are no issues found on stage and no conflicts to be resolved in the code choose “Rebase and merge” or "Squash and merge" from the merge button and let's get onto main.</span></span>

<span key="ffa3f9ca0d154abcb8d8b48323747f2c"><span offset-key="ffa3f9ca0d154abcb8d8b48323747f2c:0">If you find yourself with a merge conflict there are a number of ways to solve it. The GitHub tools are very handy or you can do it locally. When going down the local path there is a good set of instructions at </span></span><a href="https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/about-pull-request-merges" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="ee3f02a1b7cf4d0cbd50710bc5cb331b" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-5545_259-5546-237__"><span data-key="6084d3f5e2fa4e16bc05630b9b2854f4"><span data-offset-key="6084d3f5e2fa4e16bc05630b9b2854f4:0">About pull request merges</span></span></span></a><span key="9394e7ff566c4f71b26842c2ac54a910"><span offset-key="9394e7ff566c4f71b26842c2ac54a910:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">​</span></span></span>

<span key="af3cdf79978841e881ee3229325a3cd0"><span offset-key="af3cdf79978841e881ee3229325a3cd0:0">And now your code changes are on the main branch, ready to wow users with your updates. Deploy your code (if not automatically handled by GitHub events) and be ready to support any issues that arise.</span></span>
